description.text:
Created this to connect a parallel charging board inside a .50cal Ammo box and an external lipo charger.

For the bulkhead, I used ABS at 30% infill and 100% infill for the cable hook. I also scaled up by .30% to factor in ABS shrinkage. You may need to play around with your settings to get the plugs in to fit. You can use the "XT60_Bulkhead_Test" file to test you printer settings.

As for the balance plug, there is a lip the plug rest on. Install from the inside out. Depending on the extension adapter you use, you may need to detach the plug from the wires first in order to fit through the opening.

Materials needed for my build:

.50cal Ammo Box (picked up one at Harbor Freight)
XT60 Parallel charging board
XT60 Connectors
6s balance lead extension
4-M3x12mm screws
4-M3 nuts
shrink tube
3M doublesided tape (4611 VHB)

Drill small vents to prevent overheating. I would also add cement board to the side of the box you installed the bulkhead. This will help protect the bulkhead in case of a fire.

description.text:
-Update 4/13/17
-Added redesign file bottom V2.1. Took the beveled edges off the bottom surface that are along the sides (left flat and at 90 degrees) as those failed while printing on the first try... You may have better luck printing the original V2, but I did not... The bevels were purely a cosmetic touch anyhow and in no way effect the structure. Also with V2.1 added a bevel to the board mounting stand offs so there's more clearance for the board components (solder joints) on the bottom. Don't really know if there would have been any interference issues, was just more of a precaution. Also, reuploaded the top V1, V2, and V3. The fan mounting holes were WAY to large and the head on the screw to mount the fan would have just fell right through...
-Uploaded V2.1 files for the display cables, power cables, and vent sides. Just some more edge beveling to clean up the end look. Very small changes.

This control board is what came with my FLSUN Prusia I3 style printer (this box may possibly work with other control boards as well). Hated the way it originally mounted to flimsy acrylic "bars" and was out in the open with all the wires hanging out. Couldn't find a box with the features I wanted, so I designed this one myself. This is only a concept at this point as I have yet to print it.

-Can be mounted multiple ways to 20x20 extruded aluminum via mounting holes on the bottom plate with 4mm hardware.
-Board is to be mounted to the bottom plate with small screws.
-Completely prints as individual parts (bottom, top, and 4 sides). Bottom and sides are press fit together; should hold fine just by pressing together but a little glue could be used to strengthen the structure if wanted. Top is to be held on with 4 small screws.
-Posts inside allow wrapping of extra wire to take up slack (stepper motor and limit switch wires mostly...)
-Lid accommodates an 80mm fan for PLENTY of airflow over the stepper drivers, and should be a little quieter than smaller fans in similar box designs. The fan is contained INSIDE the box, not screwed to the outside. This makes the box a little larger than some others, but not outrageously large... Just use a standard 12v PC fan (most of you probably have one laying around) and cut off the plug, wire into the 12v input of the board, and the fan will always be on with the board.
-Vents are placed along the side with the drivers to help pull the air the fan brings into the box over the driver heat sinks and out of the box. Coiled up wires shouldn't affect air flow here too much...
-Access holes on the sides for USB port, 12V and stepper motor wires, and display cables.

I remixed the top and a couple sides with "MKS GEN_L V1.0" wording, but of course basic blank ones are included if you don't want the wording (I know some prefer the cleaner look, some like the extra flash). These remixed ones with wording are the V3 files.

V2 files are the final ones with cleaned up beveled edges and are going to be the preferred finished ones to use. V1 files are basic shapes and have sharp edges can be use to customized if wanted.

Let me know what you think! This is the first time I've attempted to make a part for the 3d printer itself! Feel free to play with the files and make adjustments, I just ask that if you upload your remixes you mention me in your upload :) Was made entirely using Autodesk 123D Design.

Enjoy!

This is my attempt at making an interactive feeding toy in the form of a roly polly, tumbler, or wobbler. I made two types one for small dogs, like chihuahuas or less than 10lb-dogs and another one for dogs in the 20lbs range. The design is not perfect but it does wobble and keeps them interested while there is tasty kibble or treats inside. The small version should be able to hold 1/8 cup of small kibble and the bigger version at least 1/2 cup of kibble.

The one for small dogs has a base or bottom that is mostly solid (ABS) and it is printed at half the size (scaling factor 5, bottom_threaded.stl). I printed it at 75%. The top (top_short_threaded.stl) is also printed at half the size and I used 25% infill. I did not use supports for the scaled down version.

The bigger bottom (base) part is hollow (bottom_hollow_threaded.stl) and it is printed at full-size (scale 10) and 25% infill. The top (top_short_threaded.stl) and bottom were printed with supports. To minimize printing time, I only used supports for the center of the cover. Once printed, I filled the base with stone-dust and then crazy-glued the cover. The thread worked really well on both versions.

I added images of how the parts were printed on the table of my 3D printer.

Under no circumstances (never) allow your dog to play unattended with this toy and only allow him to play with it for a maximum of 10 min at a time. If you decide to print it, I am not to be held accountable for any damage or harm that this toy may cause to your pet. Print it at your own risk and that of your pet.

title: Silica desiccant box for a filament spool

description.text:
This is a desiccant box design I use when storing my spools in vacuum bags. Each spool is stored in its own bag together with the box. This design has adjustable clip contacts so it fits most of the spools OK.

You need humidity/temperature LCD module to seal the box and keep tracking the condition of your stored filaments. The module is low cost, less than 1.5 dollar and they sell them both in Amazon.com and Aliexpress. Just search for humidity temperature LCD and you'll find one. Make sure you buy the correct module without the external sensor wire.

I use in parallel all 3 different clips with different color coding. Just print enough each type so you always have available some to fit both newly made or worn desiccant boxes.

When filling the box first use the large opening on top of the display. After the display has been installed continue topping up using the round hole with the help of the filling tool "tratti_v2.stl". The rounded hole can be sealed using an earplug.

silicabox_suoja_v3.STL is a tray that fits the silicabox. I found this useful when storing ready-to-use replacement silicaboxes in sealed plastic bags.

tuppi_assy_v2.STL
This is the 3-mm filament clip that I use together with the silica desiccant box. It has closed end which is vacuum bag friendly. The desiccant box has a recess on top that fits together with the clip. Align the clip right next to the desiccant box underneath. This way you can eliminate some sharp edges inside the vacuum bag that can potentially damage the bag.

Print settings
I have used 0.5-mm nozzle and PLA for all the items except the tray which is ABS.
Box I have printed using 0.38 mm layer height and no supports.

Here is my related thing, an electrical drying chamber for silica desiccant boxes:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2247977

Aug 18th 2017: Added a box variant "opaque" + source files. Opaque box I have intended for the use case of non-colored silica beads (no toxic moisture indicators). Also the box can be printed from ABS instead of PLA. ABS is typically available at lower price than PLA and it has a higher melting point. The latter may help recharging of the silica beads inside the container.

The elders of the internet devs and admins of reddit had some fun this April first with the introduction of r/place. It's a community generated masterpiece where each user was permitted to place one pixel of any color they choose on a canvas every five or ten minutes.

At first there was noise, and from that noise there was chaos, and from that chaos there was order... and memes.

https://www.reddit.com/r/place/

This 3D thing is an extruded heatmap of each pixel's activity for the full 72 hours of r/place. Higher points represent the most active pixel areas. A 16px Gaussian blur was added before 3D extrusion. Source heatmap was generated by /u/opl_

Notes:

Three versions are provided. The only difference between them is the amount of polygons. The "full" version has nearly 1 million triangles, and should scale up quite nicely for you non-bamboozlers.

Files are 200mm square, however I scaled my print in the picture to 50% in Slic3r.

WHOOP!

Racing style launching pad for Tiny Whoop, Blade Inductrix or similar brushed quadcopters. Launching your quad in a canted forward position allows starting at a higher speed, eliminating the need of climbing before gaining forward speed.

Update:

  • 31 Oct 2017
    • Modified ball/socket geometry for a stiffer joint.
    • Tweaked motor dimple positions to for better fitting.

Features:

  • Ball joint design allows pivoting up to approx. 20 degrees in any direction.
  • Thin arms prevents unintentional lifting your quad by ground effect, especially from idle speed / air mode.
  • Dimple shaped recesses provide just enough retention without "sinking" too deep into the launching pad.

Notes:

  • Launching in extreme angle can be problematic if your quad is in Angle / Horizon / auto-leveling modes, launching in Acro / Rate Mode is recommended, or just do the whole race in Acro, it's challenging and FUN!
  • Test ability to arm before flight! Default small_angle value in BetaFlight allows arming if your quad is canted up to 30 degrees, decrease cant angle or increase small_angle value if you have trouble with arming your quad.
  • Print upper part upside down for easier print.
  • Recommended print settings: 20% infill, 5/5/3 top/bottom/perimeters for 0.4mm nozzle at 0.2mm layer height.
  • Feel free to report in comment section if you encounter any issues with the design.

A fun heart keyring with an inner heart that can spin. The spinning joint is created with filament pieces. Easy to print! Try out different color combinations!

Assembly (see pictures):

Step 1: Print parts and cut filament. Print the Outer and Inner hearts, and cut two pieces of 1.75mm filament one 12mm long and the other 10mm long.

Step 2: Insert the filament. Insert the 12mm long piece in the bottom of the inner heart. Add the 10mm piece to the top of the inner heart (be sure to push this all the way in).

Step 3: Main assembly. Insert the bottom part of the inner heart into the outer heart first. Then snap in the top. After the top is in place, push up on the inner heart so that the filament is in a far as it will go into the outer heart.

Step 4: Add glue. Rotate the inner heart 90 degrees and add a little super glue to the joint where the filament is inserted into the outer heart.

title: RC Gravity Land Buster Rim Replacement

description.text:
A local kid had an RC car with a broken wheel. Their mom was going to get rid of it. Instead, I took it, reverse engineered the rim, and printed it out, saving the day. When searching up the Land Buster on Google, I noticed other people searched too, but there was nowhere to buy one. If you have the same kind of toy, this could be good for you too.

This is also useful if you don't like pink rims.

If this makes you smile too, please like, comment, or publish a make if you made one for someone.

I found that the PLA I used didn't have enough grip on the tire, so I wrapped 2 small rubber bands around the rim where the tire contacts. This will keep the tire from spinning on the rim. If I ever have to print one of these again, I may scale the x and y axes up just a little, to provide a better grip to the tire without rubber bands.

This was reverse engineered from an existing wheel from the Land Buster. It's not identical, it's modified to be a bit stronger, and also easier to 3d print. To minimize needed supports, I angled the exterior rim edges to 45 degrees. If you want a clean print, I suggest a bit of support in the centre, but it's not necessary. I printed mine with out supports, and the middle got a bit messy but a bit of post print clean up easily fixed it.

MINOR UPDATE [2017-05-20]
have just uploaded a cleaned-up sketchup file for anyone who want to make their own. had a bunch of duplicate components that was bloating the file up to 2mb.

MINOR UPDATE [2017-05-11]
v3 items removed. v2 should get you there.
ramp01 now has two formats 'print flat' which prints horizontal to the printer bed, or 'print in place' which prints as it would sit on the game table (45o). second option requires substantially more support but reports suggest that it prints much better. both options are available.

v2 risers and ramps modified to reduce clearance of connector pieces.
all 'double riser' connectors reduces as they created a gap between decks.
v1_ramp01 flipped over 180o to reduce print cleanup.
v3 added for risers and ramps. this creates a uniform 0.1 clearance in all directions where there is a connection (glueable). i'm not entirely convinced about v3.

MAJOR UPDATE [2017-05-05]:
new/updated models added.

based on suggestions/requests from people doing printing (thanks abchiptop).

work log...

  • checked all decks same dimension (5mm thick) [x]
  • checked filler01 and filler02 match the gaps in decks [x]
  • check riser top surfaces are same and match gaps in decks [x]
  • check riser width (vertical) as same (4mm width) [x]
  • 'bottom level' risers reduced 'foot' by 2mm [x]
  • double-sided riser top variants [x]
  • riser05, riser02; increased all underside catches by 2mm [x]
  • guard1a and guard1b; increased all underside catches by 2mm [x]
  • ladder; increased underside catches by 2mm [x]
  • handrail; increased all underside catches by 2mm [x]
  • lowguard; increased all underside catches by 2mm [x]
  • check ramp01 and ramp02 match the gaps in the decks [x]
  • recess top bar of all risers by 2mm in all directions except underside (v2) [x]
  • recess connection piece for ramp01 and ramp02 (v2) [x]
  • reduce filler01 and filler 02 (v2) [x]

should possible emphasized that the terrain set is 99% meant for construction with superglue. it's not really suitable for just shove them together and hope they stick by friction. my intent when making these was to create 3-deck long sections (including risers and handrails etc) then sort of setting them all up end to end.

--------------- old notes ----------------

an example generic/very basic terrain set for making industrial gantry terrain.

IMPORTANT: i've been making several small changes fixing bits and pieces, width or so on, so i recommend if you're planning on printing these look back just before you start to get the latest. older version may be a bit wide or wrong.

haven't played with fitting tolerances at all so likely to be a tight fit (works as confirmed by Kolden. thank you very much! http://www.thingiverse.com/make:325293).
[later] have printed out a few bits and pieces but i'm not planning on making a whole table's worth.

the decks connect to the risers using the guard(rails). probably could make a cross beam to stop wobble (spacers, done) but this is mainly a concept work. most of the pieces are 3-5mm depth which is quite chunky but the intention was to make the bits snap together strongly and be fairly stable. being chunky also allows people to glue on their own bits and pieces, rivets, skulls, mesh, controls etc.

the deck and risers should be able to print flat as a single piece. for longer pieces of decking/gantry i envisage just super-gluing together multiple deck 'squares' into single, long, permanent pieces. i've added 'filler02' which is bigger as a theoretical connector piece.
the guard/connectors may need a bit more thought in terms of easy printing. keep in mind that there will be a little stress in the 'U' that connects deck to riser when selecting printing direction (i.e. grain).

as i don't play much 28mm anymore i'm unlikely to actually print this myself.

and finally i have my 60th piece!!!

[later] more pieces added. just variations and fixes mainly. updated sketchup file included

shows the ramp connection from underneath. the ramp has a tenon that slots into the mortise on the 'deck' piece.
the mortise/tenon connections are used to join all the pieces together. the spacer01 piece is used to fill in deck slots that don't require risers or ramps.
the guard03 pieces are used to connect deck to riser where a guardrail is not required/wanted.

Purpose: To check a square tube surfaces for parallel

Background: I am building a precision linear delta which will use square stainless steel tube as the vertical ways.

Using Whitworth's 3 plate technique I can make one side of the tubing flat, but it might not be parallel to the opposite side.

This machine mounts a dial indicator so that I can measure the opposite surface's plane-ness to the flat surface I scraped. The flat surface rests on 3 skate bearings, and a spring tab in the top keeps the tubing pressed against these 3 points

Vitamins needed:
1 dial indicator
1 M6x20mm bolt
2 M5x50 mm bolts
2 M8x40 mm bolts
3 608 skate bearings
6 8mm washers

Construction:
1)print the 3 pieces: indicator mount, top and bottom
2)using the m8 bolts and washers, assemble the 3 skate bearings into the base
3)using the 2 m5 bolts, connect the indicator mount to the top and the base. the bolts go through all 3 pieces.
4)using the m6 bolt, secure the dial indicator to the indicator mount.
5)secure the base to a large stable workbench.

Instructions for use:
This is the procedure to true 3 pieces of square tubing (A,B,C) Having 4 sides (A1,A2,A3,A4,B1,B2,B3,B4,C1,C2,C3,C4)
1)Use Whitworth's 3 plate technique and a hand scraper to make sides A1,B1,C1 all flat.
2)Run A B and C through the device, with the flat (side 1) down. the dial indicator will measure the relative error between side 1 and 3 along the length of the tube. Use a hand scraper to reduce the error.
3)when A3,B3,and C3 are all parallel to A1,B1,C1, use Whitworth technique on side 3. repeat test 2 to ensure we are still parallel.

Repeat steps 1-3 for sides 2 and 4.

This should ensure the opposite sides are parallel, but does not ensure the tubes are square, they could be parallelograms in cross section.

title: 3 pin Fan temperature control box for cabinet w/LCD

description.text:
As mentioned in my other thing here
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2236078
I need a temperature control for my Prusa cabinet. I re-designed it now using an atmega 328p.

Attached are the eagle files as well as the electronics case.
As a LCD case that fits a 1602 w/I2C connector, use this one:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:90592

Important:
1) The IRF540 MosFET which is shown in the designs is not being used. I use the IRFZ 340 which is a TTL MosFET, quite cheap, but I could not find it in Eagle and did not want to draw one. Yes, it is is much much oversized, you may use a smaller one, if it is TTL N-Channel Type and pin compatible.
2) Print the top first and then cut the PCB to its final size, so you make sure the cutouts fit the connectors
3) Mark the connectors where pin 1 is, so you do not mix up directions of the connectors
4) The .ino file is for I2C Version 1 of the connector, read here:
https://arduino-info.wikispaces.com/LCD-Blue-I2C?responseToken=03e6accfe0582e9bb3beca7e9e664216e
If you have a different one, change the programm to your needs.
5) Use a long enough display cable so you can place the LCD where you like it
6) Yes, I know you should NOT use polarized capacitors with the 78L05 as it could swing. Use ceramic ones. I only had those 1µF ones lying around. Normally you SHOULD use 0.33µF as C1 and 0.01µF as C2.
7) As the 3 pin fan is controlled via a PWM pin on the atmega328p, it is hard to read the tacho signal (it is being chopped up by the PWM). I use pulse stretching to get a clear signal. This influences RPM a little when using lower PWMs.
8) Yes, the PCB requires a few wires to be connected on the top side of the PCB. The two resitors below C1 have to be connected on the left side. It is easy to overlook this, in the picture you can see it.

description.text:
This is a remix of the Thorped fan shroud and quasibrains mount for the Maker Select.
Original sources can be found here:
Shroud - http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1246425
v2.1 Mount - http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1904493

I have tried all of the major MS shrouds out there.. The DiiCooler, the Cobra, Thorped.. I liked the thorped fan the best but it bothered me how much it would move with one screw. For some reason my v2 does not have threaded holes at the top of the bearing block so I could only use the bottom one. This allowed it to rotate a bit, which would sometimes allow it to hit the print. Since there was plenty of room I extended the quasibrain mount to cover both screws on the bottom of the block. It still fits around the top of the bearing block all the way across and retains the top holes in case yours does have holes that you can use up there. The other thing I did was move the shroud a bit to the right looking from the front and slightly upward. I felt it was too close to the print and it was off center on my print nozzle. Due to this the fan is also moved to the right to match.

Since one of the mounting screws that attaches the shroud to the mount was covered by the wider bearing block mount, the holes had to be spread out a bit. Due to this, the original shroud no longer fit without widening the mounts on it. That is the only change to the shroud.

On a maker select with an enclosure I printed this in ABS using a 225deg hotend and 90deg bed. Printed at .2mm layer height with 4 perimeter shells and 4 top/bottom layers and 20% infill. My original one before remixing it was PLA and melted enough to droop completely into the bed when I forgot to take it off while printing ABS. The higher temp hot end and bed and higher ambient temp with the enclosure on was too much for it. If you will be doing higher temp materials like ABS or PETG I would recommend printing this in that material or removing it during prints of those materials if using PLA. The quasibrain mount is nice since it allows the fan to be rotated out of the mount without unscrewing it so you can access the mounting screws for easy removal.

Version History

v2

  • Add support for the original metal Joy-Con rails of your Joy-Con wrist strap to allow a greater fit for the sliding part. Shoutout to Sigismond0 for suggesting that change. The two parts have to be combined to make a print-in-place possible.

Summary

Hold your Joy-Cons comfortably in your hands by this adjustable 3-axis foldable Grip. It can also be a test for the calibration of your printer. The hinges have a .3mm tolerance to give the finished part a firm grip and avoid any flimsiness. It fits to my folding switch stand which was also designed to fit into the smallest pocket.
Everything is print-in-place. No screws, no glue no nothing. Take it from the printer, loose the hinges carefully and you are ready to go.
I would recommend printing it in PLA, since warping and sagging (bridging of the rails part) could be an issue otherwise.

Removal of the metal Rails from your Joy-Con Wrist-Stap

Remove the three phillips screws which hold the metal rail in place. Be careful not to neither loose the small plasic part nor the tiny spring which are located under the metal rail. Then take off the rails and insert them into your printed part. It will only fit in one direction (The cutout has to face the closing side). Use the original screws to tighten everything up (It's plastic so do not tighten the screws too much). Insert the Joy-Cons from the bottom to the top.

comments.text: A nifty idea.  The central axis prints beautifully, no sticking whatsoever in PETG on my MK2.  The middle axis fused and required a bit of prying with a screwdriver and dental floss to free it, but moves freely once freed.  The outer axis was just a little stuck, but came free just by moving it.  The rails, however, didn't work at all for me.  They came out way too tight for my Joy-Cons, and actually got stuck to the point I thought I was going to have to break the print to remove the Joy-Con.  I'd be interested in seeing a version that doesn't have printed rails, but instead has screw holes where you can mount the rails from the Joy-Con top bar.
comments.author: Sigismond0

comments.text:
Hi there,
thanks for sharing your printing experience. I would recommend to go with PLA, because PETG tends to sag more while bridging due to the higher printing temperature at approx. 245°C (cool down by fans takes longer). That might solve your problem with the printed rails.
Which slicer are you using? I'm using Simplify 3D. Maybe I can share my material profile with you.
I did not experience the problem of getting any of the hinges free. It comes right off the buildplate.
Make sure you have no horizontal space compensation active to keep the intended distance of the moving parts. Be sure to use a .15mm layer height so you get three layers distance of the different parts (So the layers have more time to cool down than using .2mm and have only 2 layers)
I would advice to print the joy-con holding part with PLA alone as a proof of concept to fit your Joy-Cons. Since the parts are not interconnected it should be easy to separate them. If you cannot manage this within your slicer, just drop a line here. I will upload the part separatly then.
The screw-holes for the original rails are a good idea, but I do not want to unscrew my top-bars to test it out ;) You could mix this design and put screwholes instead and give me a note. This should not be that complicated in my opinion and I would appreciate this a lot.
Cheers

title: Universal Filament Spool Holder -REMIX- Less Hardware
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Remix of in_the_garage's Universal Filament Spool Holder - http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:581788

Re-designed to use less hardware. No need for threaded rod or nuts. I would still recommend the aluminium tubes. But I've included printable tubes as an option.

Press fit four 608, 608-Z, 608-RS, 608-ZZ or 608-2RS bearings onto the two sides first. Then press fit the aluminum tubes or printed tubes. Install the base last to hold everything together. Adding four silicone stick-on feet to the bottom of the assembled holder is recommended but optional.

I could have removed material and made this design more economical on filament. But I wanted to maintain the original look as much as possible.

Remixed in TinkerCAD: https://tinkercad.com/things/0T5H7uTWUVM

EDIT: I've changed the default orientation of the Side piece.

Added some photos of the first print. I need to add tolerance to the keys and key slots. I had to do a fair bit of filing to get them to fit. But it's a good snug fit. Still waiting on bearings and need to get the aluminium.
Modular design and hardware reduction inspired by Chrlee's Ball Bearing Filament Holder - http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2221639

Bearings

608 bearings are available on Amazon, AliExpress or your local skateboard shop. Some sporting goods stores may carry them. Or sacrifice an old pair of inline skates from a thrift store.

About bearings: All that Z, ZZ, RS, 2RS stuff is just telling you whether or not the bearing has metal shields (Z) or rubber shields (RS) on one or both sides. For this purpose, it won't matter much. Another thing you'll run into are ABEC ratings which really just tell you about the acceptable tolerances. Anything above ABEC-5 is probably serious overkill for this project. Use what you have, prefer or can get affordably.

A 608 bearing is has a 22mm outside diameter, 7mm width and an 8mm diameter hole.

Aluminium Tube

If you're looking for a source for Aluminum Tubes, Metal Supermarkets (https://www.metalsupermarkets.com) seems to be pretty well represented across North America. If you've got suppliers for other parts of the world, drop them in the comments.

You'll need two Aluminum (or Stainless Steel) Tubes with an outside diameter (OD) of 1" (or 25mm) and an inside diameter (ID) of 7/8" (or 22mm) and a length of 3 7/8" (or 98mm.)

1" OD is a pretty common tubing size. It shouldn't be too hard to get. Just remember to check the ID will fit your 22mm bearing snuggly.

(The length of the printed roller is 97mm because I took off a millimeter for tolerance.)

title: Customizable Wanhao i3Plus i3 Plus Duplicator Upgrade Cooling Duct

description.text:
Two variants of a cooler for the Wanhao Duplicator i3 Plus

  • "SimpleCooler" is like the standard cooler, just slightly less high - my original one is too close to the build plate and to the things I build
  • "CoolingDuct" has an open cooling ring around the hot end of the printer - this improves print quality as it cools down the extruded filament faster than the original cooler. Effects are:
    • better top surfaces, less pillowing
    • cleaner overhangs
    • less stringing

Both can be installed without any extra material - no extra screws, no different fan - the original screws and fan can be used! However, to improve mounting strength, two M3x10 screws are recommended for attaching to the mounting arm.

Improved v1.1: I've moved the screw positions for the mounting arm further to the right so that they don't collide with the fan screws.

This thing is customizable: For the cooling duct, you can customize

  • the tilt of the cooling ring to compensate a bended mounting arm
  • the angle of the cooling ring - 0 means no ring, 360 means a full ring.
